Russian officials investigate the scene of a car explosion that killed Darya Dugina, daughter of a Russian political scientist and ally of President Vladimir Putin, on August 21. | Investigative Committee of Russia via AP
    

  
A Russian politics expert explains how much is still unknown about the murder of Darya Dugina.
 Over the weekend, a car exploded along a Moscow highway. Inside was Darya Dugina, the daughter of an ultranationalist ally of Russian President Vladimir Putin. 
Dugina, though lower profile than her father Aleksandr Dugin, espoused many similar nationalist and pro-war beliefs and had been sanctioned by the United States for running a disinformation website. Russia is blaming Ukraine for Dugina’s death, and it’s already prompting recriminations between the two countries…
articles.title: Everything we actually know about the Moscow car bombing

articles.description:
The first photos have been released from China’s raid on Chinese-Australian journalist Cheng Lei. 

Ms Lei has now been detained by Chinese authorities for two years following her arrest for leaking state secrets, and there have been serious concerns for her health and safety following her detainment. 

The new images that have been obtained have revealed what her apartment looked like when she was arrested, according to Sky News host James Morrow.

“They took her passport, her computer ... we get a sense of what it was like,” Mr Morrow told Sky News Australia. 

In the Daily Telegraph's new film ‘Disappeared – The Cheng Lei Story’, the photos are just one revelation. 

Ms Lei's family and friend’s plea to the Chinese government has been for it to show some compassion and let her return home to Australia.

Mr Morrow believes there is hope that after the Chinese national party congress later this year, there may be some softening of this relationship.

Was the Federal Bureau of Investigation justified in raiding Donald Trump’s Mar-a-Lago residence?  The judge who issued the warrant for Mar-a-Lago has signaled that he is likely to release a redacted version of the supporting affidavit.  But the warrant itself suggests the answer is probably no – the FBI had no legal cause for the raid.
The warrant authorized the FBI to seize “all physical documents and records constituting evidence, contraband, proceeds of crime, or other illegally possessed in violation of 18 USC §§793, 2071, or 1519” (emphasis added).  These three criminal statutes all deal with the possession and handling of documents containing national security information, public records, or documents relevant to an investigation or other matters before a federal agency or the courts.

articles.description:
According to local media 36kr.com, Chinese tech conglomerate Tencent recently received a new patent for a blockchain-based missing persons poster.  The patent took nearly three years to issue from the date of its first submission in December 2019.
The paten consists of a request to generate data when the user submits that a person has disappeared.  The proposal is then unveiled publicly on the blockchain for verification.  Once a consensus has been reached regarding the request, it is then stored in the public ledger and transmitted to the nodes for dissemination to a wider audience.  Tencent said in the patent application that the design aims to improve the efficiency of finding missing persons.
Tencent was an early adopter of blockchain technology among big tech companies, particularly when it came to exploring possibilities for integration with payment technology;  though his efforts have been hampered somewhat by China’s strict crypto regulations.  Yet his “FISCO BCOS” coinless blockchain jointly developed with Chinese telecom giant Huawei from 2018 for building decentralized applications remains active to this day. 
Early July, Tencent close one of its non-fungible token platforms after the Chinese government clarified that it does not allow users to conduct private transactions after purchase, as well as a drop in sales.
China is currently embarking on a centralized approach to blockchain technology, with a policy significantly favoring its central bank digital currency in digital yuan (e-CNY) instead of digital tokens developed by private companies.  Last week, the country rolled out its first-ever e-CNY-enabled social security card, which allows social assistance to be directly deposited into the recipient’s digital yuan account and used for expenses.

Reuters: Exclusive-U.S. commits to Afghan asset talks despite frustration with Taliban - sources 
WASHINGTON (Reuters) - U.S. President Joe Biden's administration will press ahead with talks on releasing billions of dollars in Afghanistan's foreign-held assets despite the late al Qaeda leader's presence in Kabul and foot-dragging by the Taliban and Afghan central bank, according to three sources with knowledge of the situation.
